Problem Set 5 was the most educational assignment in MAE 3240 because it required applying multiple heat transfer concepts in an integrated, realistic context. Working through the cylindrical pin fin problem, from deriving the temperature distribution to analyzing an entire fin array and thermal resistance network, gave me a concrete understanding of how extended surfaces are used in engineering practice to enhance heat dissipation. Seeing how the fin array reduced the heater temperature by nearly 89°C made the theory feel tangible and meaningful.

The second problem on lumped capacitance with Joule heating deepened my understanding of transient heat transfer by extending the standard method to include internal heat generation. Deriving the temperature expression T(t) from first principles and finding a clean time constant of τ = 1 s reinforced how dimensional reasoning and energy balances connect to real physical behavior. These techniques, fin analysis, thermal resistance networks, and lumped capacitance, are fundamental tools I expect to use throughout my engineering career in applications ranging from electronics cooling to power systems design.

